{"agent_memory": {"title": "Barrel re-exporting untracked sibling modules = Critical build-integrity gate (ai-bookkeeper ledger)", "content": "Recurring pattern in ai-bookkeeper team handoffs: a scoped commit (e.g. b29eeaa for ADR 0002) commits its own new module + ADR but also adds barrel (src/features/ledger/index.ts) re-exports for SIBLING modules (amount.ts, ingest.ts) that were never committed (still untracked from a prior work order). Tests pass locally because the files exist in the working tree, but a clean checkout / CI fails on module resolution + tsc. As reviewer: ALWAYS verify barrel imports against git history (`git log -- <path>`), not just the working tree, before approving. This is a Critical correctness/build finding → REQUEST_CHANGES even when the new module's own logic is flawless. The fix is a prerequisite commit for the sibling modules, not widening the original commit. The Dev Clone correctly flagged it rather than auto-fixing; the gap persists until a human lands amount.ts/ingest.ts.", "category": "learned", "importance": 5, "tags": ["code-review", "ai-bookkeeper", "ledger", "barrel-exports", "build-integrity", "adr-0002", "request-changes"]}}

{"knowledge_annotation": {"scope": "global", "note": "When reviewing a commit for build integrity, verify barrel/index re-export targets against GIT HISTORY (git log -- <path>), not the working tree. A commit can pass local tests while being non-self-contained if the barrel references untracked sibling files that exist on disk but were never committed — a clean checkout/CI then fails tsc and module resolution. In ai-bookkeeper, test runner is `npm test` (tsx --test, node:test) and `git status --short` reliably reveals untracked '??' modules.", "confidence": 0.9}}

